latestPosts.caption:
Woke up this morning thinking of this moment - barefaced in a bathrobe, overlooking the Caspian. 

Waking up early is probably my most sacred daily ritual. It’s a habit drilled into me from boarding school that I carried through university into adulthood & to now, when I set my own hours and still choose to be up before the world starts talking at me. Some of that is muscle memory, but maybe, most of all, it’s a reflection of my mum. She’s been waking up at 5:30 a.m. for as long as I can remember. And always so intentional with her time. It’s definitely something I resisted as a teenager, but find myself seeking now. I notice that it gives me a greater sense of ownership over my day. 

So I love that the mornings are always mine. Even on holiday. Actually, especially on holiday. There’s just something about watching the sky shift colours over a new city. 

Most days, those first couple of hours are reserved for poring over the news. I know my life looks very different now but it’s how I stay in touch with the version of me who studied international relations & development, worked in policy, and hopes to get back to it someday. In fact, I know I will.
